  "text": "Though there is certainly of an increased risk of bleeding, percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) has been performed successfully in patients with thrombocytopenia (reported most often in the case of idiopathic thrombocytopenia); bare metal stents have generally been preferred to drug-eluting stents in order to limit the duration of dual anti-platelet therapy with aspirin and clopidogrel [CITATION_1] . Use of aspirin and balloon angioplasty alone was complicated by restenosis in one case, requiring initiation of clopidogrel and stent placement [CITATION_2] .",
